================================================================================
ADVANCED QUALITY AUDIT — ARCHITECTURE, API DESIGN & EXTENSIBILITY
================================================================================
Repository   : szmyty/visionlog
Audit Date   : 2026-04-01T08:04:48Z
Auditor      : GitHub Copilot (second-pass advanced audit)
Package      : visionlog 0.1.1
Description  : A universal structured logging library for analytics tracking
Language     : Python (^3.8)
Build System : Poetry
Prior Audit  : audit-20260331T180454.log (production readiness baseline)
================================================================================

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
-----------------
This second-pass audit focuses on internal design quality, architectural
soundness, and long-term maintainability. The baseline production-readiness
issues flagged in audit-20260331T180454.log (missing tests, CI, bare
exceptions, privacy model) have since been addressed. This audit assumes those
fixes are in place and looks at the deeper structural and design questions that
will determine whether visionlog can evolve cleanly into a mature library.

The central problems found in this pass are:

  1. get_logger carries 10 parameters with no grouping abstraction — it will
     become unmaintainable as features are added and is hostile to refactoring.
  2. structlog.configure() runs at module import time as a global side effect,
     making it impossible to have multiple independent logger configurations in
     the same process.
  3. loguru is imported and reconfigured on every get_logger() call, adding
     startup latency and creating confusing dual-framework output with no
     documented rationale.
  4. add_common_fields always injects app_name = "visionlog" regardless of the
     service_name argument, silently discarding the caller's intent.
  5. The enrichment pipeline (IP, geo, device) is entangled inside get_logger
     with no abstraction; every new enrichment type requires modifying the same
     function signature.

Overall Architecture Quality Score: 4 / 10

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FINDINGS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## CATEGORY 1 — API DESIGN
----------------------------

[HIGH]    API-001 — get_logger has 10 parameters with no grouping abstraction
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:123-134
  Detail  : The public factory function accepts service_name, user_id,
            session_id, ip_address, device_info, user_agent, geo_info,
            enable_tracing, privacy_mode, and disable_network — ten positional
            and keyword arguments. There is no way to construct a configuration
            object and pass it around, store it, or reuse it across call sites.
            Adding any new enrichment type (e.g., region, tenant_id, env) will
            require appending yet another parameter to an already-wide function
            signature, increasing the combinatorial test surface.
  Action  : Introduce a LoggerConfig dataclass (or TypedDict for Python 3.8
            compatibility) that groups related parameters into logical buckets:
              - IdentityConfig: user_id, session_id, service_name
              - NetworkConfig: ip_address, geo_info, disable_network
              - DeviceConfig: device_info, user_agent
              - PrivacyConfig: privacy_mode
            get_logger should accept either individual kwargs (for backward
            compatibility) or a config object. This also enables serialisation,
            logging of the config itself, and easier testing.

[HIGH]    API-002 — add_common_fields ignores service_name; always injects
            "visionlog" as app_name
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:86-91
  Detail  : The structlog processor add_common_fields unconditionally sets
            event_dict["app_name"] = "visionlog". Because structlog processors
            share no state with get_logger, the service_name argument passed
            to get_logger is only attached as the "service" field via
            logger.bind(service=service_name) and never reaches app_name. Users
            who call get_logger("my-api") will always see app_name="visionlog"
            in their logs — a silent data quality bug.
  Action  : Either (a) rename the field from app_name to service and remove the
            duplicate binding, or (b) pass service_name into the processor via
            a closure or structlog's contextvars support, so that app_name
            reflects the actual service. Option (a) is simpler and avoids the
            two-field redundancy (service + app_name) entirely.

[MEDIUM]  API-003 — serialize_json accepts *args/**kwargs but ignores them
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:16-18
  Detail  : The signature `serialize_json(record, *args, **kwargs)` accepts
            arbitrary extra arguments that are silently dropped. structlog's
            JSONRenderer passes a single positional argument; the variadic
            signature adds noise and hides the actual contract.
  Action  : Remove the *args/**kwargs and use the minimal correct signature:
            `serialize_json(record: Any) -> str`. Add a return type annotation.

[MEDIUM]  API-004 — enable_tracing is deprecated but carries no removal
            timeline or DeprecationWarning
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:131, 170-172
  Detail  : The parameter enable_tracing is described as deprecated since
            0.2.0 and documented to have "no effect", yet it emits no
            DeprecationWarning and there is no documented target version for
            removal. Parameters that silently do nothing erode API trust.
  Action  : Emit `warnings.warn(..., DeprecationWarning, stacklevel=2)` when
            enable_tracing is passed with any value. Document the removal
            target version (e.g., "will be removed in 1.0.0") both in the
            docstring and in CHANGELOG.md.

[MINOR]   API-005 — __all__ in __init__.py exports only get_logger, hiding
            useful public types
  Files   : visionlog/__init__.py:3
  Detail  : Only get_logger is exported. When users want to use
            serialize_json, add_common_fields, or type hints for a future
            LoggerConfig, they must import from the internal
            visionlog.visionlog submodule — a leaky implementation detail.
  Action  : Expand __all__ to include all symbols that are intentionally
            public. Consider re-exporting from visionlog/__init__.py so
            callers always use `from visionlog import X` rather than
            `from visionlog.visionlog import X`.

## CATEGORY 2 — ARCHITECTURE & MODULARITY
-------------------------------------------

[HIGH]    ARCH-001 — structlog.configure() runs at module import time as a
            global side effect
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:110-121
  Detail  : The call to structlog.configure() at module level executes the
            moment the package is imported. This creates several problems:
              (a) Any application that imports visionlog and also uses
                  structlog directly will have its structlog configuration
                  silently overwritten.
              (b) Unit tests cannot test different processor chains without
                  carefully resetting global state.
              (c) It is impossible to instantiate two loggers with different
                  processor pipelines in the same process.
            This is the most architecturally significant problem in the library.
  Action  : Move structlog.configure() inside get_logger and guard it with a
            module-level flag (_configured = False) so it runs at most once on
            first use. Alternatively, adopt structlog's BoundLoggerLazy pattern
            and configure structlog per-instance rather than globally.
            Long-term: expose a configure_visionlog() function that applications
            can call explicitly, making the side effect opt-in rather than
            implicit.

[HIGH]    ARCH-002 — loguru is configured inside get_logger on every call
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:175-176
  Detail  : Every call to get_logger() executes:
              loguru.logger.remove()
              loguru.logger.add(sys.stdout, format="{message}", serialize=False)
            This means every logger creation re-initialises the global loguru
            sink. In applications that create multiple loggers (e.g., per
            request in a web framework), this repeatedly reconfigures loguru,
            which is not thread-safe and adds latency. The output from loguru
            and structlog will also be duplicated on stdout. The README makes
            no mention of loguru, so the dual-framework design is undocumented
            and likely unintentional.
  Action  : Clarify the intended role of loguru. If the goal is fallback
            output, move loguru configuration to a module-level initialisation
            block (like structlog.configure) guarded by a flag, so it runs once.
            If loguru serves no unique purpose that structlog's
            stdlib.LoggerFactory does not already provide, remove the loguru
            dependency entirely.

[MEDIUM]  ARCH-003 — visionlog.py mixes four distinct concerns in one file
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py
  Detail  : The single module contains:
              - HTTP utility functions (get_public_ip, get_geo_info)
              - Device fingerprinting (get_device_info)
              - structlog processor functions (add_common_fields, add_otel_context,
                serialize_json)
              - Logger factory and global configuration (get_logger,
                structlog.configure)
            This violates the Single Responsibility Principle. Changes to the
            HTTP layer require touching the same file as changes to the
            processor pipeline.
  Action  : Split into logical submodules:
              - visionlog/enrichers/network.py  (get_public_ip, get_geo_info)
              - visionlog/enrichers/device.py   (get_device_info)
              - visionlog/processors.py         (serialize_json, add_common_fields,
                                                  add_otel_context)
              - visionlog/logger.py             (get_logger, configure)
            Keep visionlog/__init__.py as the public re-export surface.

[MEDIUM]  ARCH-004 — if __name__ == "__main__" block in library module makes
            live network requests
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:207-222
  Detail  : The __main__ block inside the library module calls get_logger with
            ip_address=True, device_info=True, and geo_info=True without
            privacy_mode=False, meaning it would silently skip those features
            under the default privacy_mode=True. More importantly, running
            `python -m visionlog.visionlog` in a CI or restricted environment
            would attempt live HTTP requests. This block was flagged in the
            prior audit (STR-002) and should be moved.
  Action  : Delete the __main__ block. Move the example to
            examples/basic_usage.py (which already exists). If a smoke-test
            entry point is needed, add a `__main__.py` at the package level
            that the CLI can invoke.

## CATEGORY 3 — DESIGN PATTERNS
----------------------------------

[HIGH]    PAT-001 — No pluggable enricher abstraction; every new field
            requires modifying get_logger's signature
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:123-205
  Detail  : The current design hard-codes three enrichment types (IP/geo,
            device, OTel tracing). Adding a fourth (e.g., environment, region,
            tenant, feature flags) requires:
              (a) Adding new parameters to get_logger
              (b) Adding new conditional logic inside get_logger
              (c) Updating tests, docs, and type stubs
            This is the open/closed principle violation — the function is not
            closed for modification.
  Action  : Introduce an Enricher protocol or abstract base class:
              class Enricher(Protocol):
                  def enrich(self, logger: BoundLogger) -> BoundLogger: ...
            get_logger can accept an optional list of enrichers. Built-in
            enrichers (NetworkEnricher, DeviceEnricher) live in their own
            modules. Third-party code can provide custom enrichers without
            touching the core API. This makes future enrichment types
            zero-cost to add.

[MEDIUM]  PAT-002 — Global singleton pattern for structlog configuration is
            implicit and fragile
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:110-121
  Detail  : The module-level structlog.configure() creates an implicit global
            singleton configuration without any of the safeguards associated
            with the Singleton pattern: no thread-safety, no reconfiguration
            prevention, no way to reset in tests. The tests in test_tracing.py
            already work around this by checking processor identity rather than
            re-running configure.
  Action  : Make the singleton explicit. A module-level _CONFIGURED flag
            (defaulting to False) combined with a public configure() function
            gives callers control over when the side effect fires, while still
            preventing accidental double-configuration.

[MINOR]   PAT-003 — No builder or fluent interface for incremental logger
            construction
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:123-205
  Detail  : get_logger returns a fully-configured BoundLogger. If a caller
            wants to conditionally add fields (e.g., add user_id only if
            authenticated), they must call logger.bind() manually and know the
            internal field names. A fluent builder would express this more
            clearly:
              logger = (
                  LoggerBuilder("my-api")
                  .with_user("user_42")
                  .with_session("sess_123")
                  .build()
              )
  Action  : Consider a LoggerBuilder class as an optional ergonomic layer on
            top of get_logger. This is a low-priority improvement but would
            significantly improve usability for complex configurations.

## CATEGORY 4 — CONFIGURATION & FLEXIBILITY
---------------------------------------------

[HIGH]    CFG-001 — Output format is hardcoded to JSON with no way to
            configure alternative renderers
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:116
  Detail  : structlog.processors.JSONRenderer is the only renderer used, and
            it is hard-coded into the processor chain at import time. There is
            no way for users to select plain-text output (useful for
            development), logfmt output, or a custom renderer without forking
            the library or monkey-patching structlog's global configuration.
  Action  : Accept an optional renderer parameter in get_logger (or in a
            configure_visionlog() function), defaulting to JSONRenderer. Ship
            pre-built renderer options:
              - "json"      → JSONRenderer(serializer=serialize_json)  [default]
              - "console"   → structlog.dev.ConsoleRenderer()
              - "logfmt"    → a custom LogfmtRenderer if desired
            This turns a hard-coded implementation detail into a documented
            feature.

[MEDIUM]  CFG-002 — No way to inject custom structlog processors
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:110-121
  Detail  : The processor chain [TimeStamper, add_log_level, add_common_fields,
            add_otel_context, JSONRenderer] is fixed. Users who want to add a
            custom field extractor, a log sampler, or a redaction processor
            have no hook to do so.
  Action  : Expose an extra_processors: Optional[List[Processor]] parameter
            in configure_visionlog() that is inserted between add_otel_context
            and the final renderer. This gives users the ability to extend the
            pipeline without replacing the whole configuration.

[MINOR]   CFG-003 — Timeout for HTTP enrichment calls is not configurable
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:30, 46
  Detail  : The timeout for both httpx.get calls is hard-coded to 5.0 seconds.
            This is a reasonable default but should be configurable for
            environments where network latency varies significantly.
  Action  : Add an http_timeout: float = 5.0 parameter to get_public_ip and
            get_geo_info (or to the network enricher config).

## CATEGORY 5 — LOGGING & OBSERVABILITY DESIGN
-------------------------------------------------

[HIGH]    OBS-001 — app_name field is static "visionlog" and duplicates the
            "service" field without adding value
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:86-91, 178
  Detail  : Each log record contains:
              - "service": <value of service_name parameter>  (from logger.bind)
              - "app_name": "visionlog"                        (from add_common_fields)
            These are redundant. app_name is the library name, not the
            application name, which makes the field actively misleading for
            users running visionlog in their own application.
  Action  : Remove the static app_name field from add_common_fields. If a
            library-version field is desired for debugging, use a well-known
            name such as "logger_library": "visionlog" or simply remove it.
            The "service" field already carries the application identity.

[MEDIUM]  OBS-002 — log_level is injected as a separate field but structlog
            already includes a "level" key via add_log_level
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:90
  Detail  : The structlog processor chain includes structlog.processors.add_log_level
            (which adds "level") and add_common_fields (which adds "log_level").
            Both carry the same information. Log consumers (Elasticsearch,
            Datadog, Splunk) that key on "level" may ignore the custom
            "log_level" field.
  Action  : Remove the "log_level" injection from add_common_fields. The
            built-in "level" field from structlog.processors.add_log_level is
            the standard field and is sufficient.

[MINOR]   OBS-003 — No hostname or environment field injected by default
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:86-91
  Detail  : Production log systems benefit from hostname and environment
            (prod/staging/dev) fields in every log record. These are typically
            cheap to populate at startup (os.uname, os.environ) and are
            critical for triage in multi-host deployments.
  Action  : Add optional hostname: bool = False and environment:
            Optional[str] = None parameters to get_logger (or to the enricher
            pipeline). Hostname can be populated via socket.gethostname().

[MINOR]   OBS-004 — log_id uses UUID4 with no way to supply a custom ID
            generator
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:88
  Detail  : The log_id field is always generated via str(uuid.uuid4()). Some
            applications use ULID, KSUID, or their own monotonic ID schemes.
            There is no way to override the generator without forking the library.
  Action  : Accept an optional id_generator: Callable[[], str] parameter in
            add_common_fields or in the configuration, defaulting to
            lambda: str(uuid.uuid4()).

## CATEGORY 6 — ERROR HANDLING STRATEGY
-----------------------------------------

[MEDIUM]  ERR-001 — warnings.warn is used for enrichment failures but is
            often silenced in production environments
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:31-32, 54-55
  Detail  : Failed calls to get_public_ip and get_geo_info emit warnings.warn,
            which is filtered by default in many production configurations
            (PYTHONWARNINGS=ignore, or applications that consume warnings via
            logging.captureWarnings). A logging library that silently degrades
            is unacceptable when operators need to know enrichment is failing.
  Action  : Replace warnings.warn with a structlog internal logger (or Python
            stdlib logging.getLogger("visionlog").warning) so that enrichment
            failures appear in the application's log stream alongside normal
            log output. This makes degraded enrichment visible without crashing
            the application.

[MEDIUM]  ERR-002 — DeviceDetector constructor and .parse() call are not
            wrapped in error handling
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:73
  Detail  : `DeviceDetector(user_agent).parse()` is called without any
            exception handling. Malformed user-agent strings, corrupt database
            files, or library bugs will raise unhandled exceptions and crash
            the logger-creation path. For a library that is called during
            application startup, this is a high-severity failure mode.
  Action  : Wrap the DeviceDetector call in a try/except block and fall back
            to the platform-based defaults on any exception, emitting a
            warning (see ERR-001 for the preferred warning mechanism).

[MINOR]   ERR-003 — serialize_json does not handle non-serialisable objects
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:16-18
  Detail  : orjson.dumps will raise orjson.JSONEncodeError (a subclass of
            TypeError) if the log record contains a non-serialisable value
            (e.g., a datetime without a registered handler, a custom object).
            This will crash the structlog processor chain silently (structlog
            may suppress the error depending on configuration).
  Action  : Add a try/except orjson.JSONEncodeError block that falls back to
            a safe representation (e.g., str(record)) and emits a warning.
            Alternatively, use orjson.OPT_NON_STR_KEYS | orjson.OPT_SERIALIZE_UUID
            to handle common edge cases automatically.

## CATEGORY 7 — PERFORMANCE CONSIDERATIONS
--------------------------------------------

[HIGH]    PERF-001 — loguru.logger.remove() + loguru.logger.add() runs on
            every get_logger() call
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:175-176
  Detail  : Every invocation of get_logger() re-removes all loguru sinks and
            adds a new one. In a web application handling 1000 req/s where each
            request creates a logger, this means 1000 loguru reconfigurations
            per second. loguru's remove() and add() operations acquire an
            internal lock, making this a latency and contention issue.
  Action  : Guard loguru configuration with a module-level flag (same pattern
            as the structlog fix for ARCH-001) so it runs at most once per
            process lifetime. If loguru is removed entirely (ARCH-002), this
            issue disappears.

[MEDIUM]  PERF-002 — Public IP is fetched on every get_logger() call with no
            caching
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:191
  Detail  : When ip_address=True and privacy_mode=False, get_public_ip() makes
            a live HTTP request to api64.ipify.org on every call to get_logger.
            In applications that create a logger per request (common in async
            web frameworks), this produces one external HTTP call per request,
            adding latency and creating a dependency on an external service at
            every log initialisation.
  Action  : Cache the resolved public IP at the module level with an optional
            TTL (e.g., cache_ip_for: int = 300 seconds). A simple
            functools.lru_cache with maxsize=1 on get_public_ip is the
            minimal fix, though a time-based TTL is more correct in
            long-running processes where the IP can change.

[MINOR]   PERF-003 — structlog.configure() called with cache_logger_on_first_use=True
            but loguru re-init on every call undermines this
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:120, 175-176
  Detail  : cache_logger_on_first_use=True is a structlog optimisation that
            freezes the processor chain after the first log call. However,
            the loguru reconfiguration on every get_logger call resets the
            underlying sink, potentially causing the cached structlog state to
            reference a stale loguru handler. The interaction is subtle but
            can lead to dropped log entries in threaded applications.
  Action  : Resolving PERF-001 (guarding loguru init) and ARCH-002 (clarifying
            loguru's role) will resolve this interaction.

## CATEGORY 8 — DEPENDENCY DESIGN
------------------------------------

[HIGH]    DEP-001 — loguru's role relative to structlog is undefined and the
            two frameworks overlap completely
  Files   : pyproject.toml:24, visionlog/visionlog.py:4, 175-176
  Detail  : Both loguru and structlog are required dependencies. structlog
            provides the processor pipeline, JSON rendering, and the public
            BoundLogger API. loguru is used only to add a stdout sink with
            format="{message}". structlog's own LoggerFactory and PrintLoggerFactory
            already provide stdout output. Having both frameworks makes the
            dependency graph unnecessarily heavy, creates confusing dual-output
            behaviour, and presents a maintenance burden when either library
            releases breaking changes.
  Action  : Determine the intended output path and commit to one framework.
            If structlog is the primary framework (as the public API suggests),
            remove loguru as a dependency. If loguru is preferred for its
            structured output features, use it as the sole framework. Document
            the rationale in ARCHITECTURE.md or CONTRIBUTING.md.

[MEDIUM]  DEP-002 — httpx is a required dependency but is only needed for
            optional PII enrichment features
  Files   : pyproject.toml:31, visionlog/visionlog.py:7
  Detail  : httpx is unconditionally installed as a required dependency, but
            it is only used when privacy_mode=False and ip_address=True or
            geo_info=True. The majority of users who never enable PII
            enrichment still pay the httpx install cost (~1.5 MB wheel).
  Action  : Move httpx to an optional extras group:
              [tool.poetry.extras]
              network = ["httpx"]
            Guard get_public_ip and get_geo_info with an ImportError check
            like the existing DeviceDetector guard. This follows the same
            pattern already used for device-detector and is consistent with
            the library's stated optional-enrichment philosophy.

[MINOR]   DEP-003 — No abstraction layer around httpx in network enrichment
            functions
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:30, 46
  Detail  : httpx.get is called directly without an adapter or client
            abstraction. Tests must patch visionlog.visionlog.httpx.get,
            tying tests to the specific HTTP library. If httpx is ever
            swapped for aiohttp or the stdlib urllib, every test that
            patches httpx must be updated.
  Action  : Extract a _fetch_json(url: str, timeout: float) -> dict helper
            that wraps httpx.get. Tests patch _fetch_json rather than httpx.get
            directly. This also makes it easier to add retry logic, custom
            headers, or proxy support in one place.

## CATEGORY 9 — CLI DESIGN
----------------------------

[HIGH]    CLI-001 — CLI exposes only --message and provides no access to any
            get_logger options
  Files   : visionlog/cli.py
  Detail  : The CLI is a thin wrapper that calls get_logger() with all defaults
            and logs a single message. It does not expose --service-name,
            --log-level, --user-id, --session-id, or any of the library's
            enrichment options. This makes the CLI unsuitable for:
              - Quickly testing enrichment behaviour from the command line
              - Scripted log injection in shell pipelines
              - Smoke-testing the library in CI without writing Python code
  Action  : Expand the CLI with options mirroring the core get_logger API:
              --service-name TEXT       Service name for the log record
              --level [debug|info|warning|error|critical]  Log level
              --user-id TEXT            User identity field
              --session-id TEXT         Session identity field
              --no-privacy              Disable privacy mode (enable PII)
              --ip / --no-ip            Auto-fetch public IP (requires --no-privacy)
              --geo / --no-geo          Fetch geo info (requires --no-privacy)
            Use click.option defaults that mirror get_logger defaults so the
            CLI and library stay in sync.

[MEDIUM]  CLI-002 — CLI command is named "log" which conflicts with Python's
            stdlib logging module in shell tab-completion and import namespace
  Files   : visionlog/cli.py:6
  Detail  : The click command is named "log". While click commands are not
            Python symbols, the name creates cognitive dissonance for developers
            who associate "log" with Python's built-in logging. The entry point
            is correctly named "visionlog-cli" but the subcommand is "log",
            so invocation is `visionlog-cli log` — the repetition is awkward
            when only one subcommand exists.
  Action  : Either rename the command to "emit" or "send" for clarity, or
            restructure the CLI as a single command (no subcommand) where
            `visionlog-cli --message "..."` works directly. The latter matches
            the current single-purpose design.

[MINOR]   CLI-003 — CLI produces no output on success and no error on failure
  Files   : visionlog/cli.py:6-8
  Detail  : The CLI function has no return value handling. If get_logger raises
            (e.g., ImportError from device-detector), the exception propagates
            unhandled through click and produces a stack trace rather than a
            user-friendly error message.
  Action  : Wrap the CLI body in a try/except block and use click.echo(...,
            err=True) + sys.exit(1) for clean error reporting.

## CATEGORY 10 — FUTURE EXTENSIBILITY
---------------------------------------

[HIGH]    EXT-001 — Adding new enrichment fields requires modifying the
            get_logger signature, breaking the open/closed principle
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:123-205
  Detail  : See PAT-001. This finding specifically notes that any third-party
            library that integrates with visionlog (e.g., a Django plugin, a
            FastAPI middleware) cannot add enrichment fields without either:
              (a) Forking the library
              (b) Calling logger.bind() manually after construction, which
                  bypasses any validation, documentation, or observability in
                  the enrichment pipeline
  Action  : Implement the Enricher protocol described in PAT-001. Additionally,
            provide an entry-points hook (importlib.metadata) so installed
            packages can register enrichers that are automatically picked up
            by get_logger, following the pattern used by pytest plugins,
            Flask extensions, etc.

[MEDIUM]  EXT-002 — Output format cannot be changed without modifying
            module-level global state
  Files   : visionlog/visionlog.py:110-121
  Detail  : See CFG-001. Because structlog.configure() runs at import time,
            even if a user calls structlog.configure() themselves afterward,
            they must know to do so after importing visionlog. Any library that
            imports visionlog as a transitive dependency will silently hijack
            the host application's structlog configuration.
  Action  : Resolve ARCH-001 first. Then expose a configure_visionlog(
            renderer="json", extra_processors=None) function that can be called
            explicitly, making visionlog a well-behaved guest in applications
            that also use structlog.

[MINOR]   EXT-003 — No versioned public API or stability guarantees
  Files   : visionlog/__init__.py, pyproject.toml
  Detail  : The library is at version 0.1.1 with no documented API stability
            promise. Users who build on visionlog cannot determine whether any
            symbol is considered stable or internal. Python convention is to
            use an underscore prefix for internal symbols, but visionlog
            currently exposes all module-level functions without distinction.
  Action  : Document the public API contract in README.md and in __init__.py's
